Introduction

Defining the problem and assembling a dataset

[ Dataset ]
Breast Cancer Wisconsin (Diagnostic)

[ Source ]
UCI Machine Learning Repository

[ Classification ]
Binary classification
M = malignant, B = benign

  • Malignant tumors are cancerous and can grow rapidly, invade and destroy nearby tissues.
  • Benign tumors are noncancerous and do not invade nearby tissue or spread to other parts of the body.

[ Attribute information ]
Number of attribues: 32
Field 1: ID Number
Field 2: Diagnosis
Fields 3 - 32: Ten real-valued features computed for each cell nucleus

The mean, standard error (SE), and the mean of the three largest values (Worst) of these features were computed for each image, resulting in 30 features. E.g. Field 3 is Mean Radius, field 13 is Radius SE, field 23 is Worst Radius.

Feature descriptions:

Feature Description
Feature 1 Radius (mean of distances from center to points on the perimeter)
Feature 2 Texture (standard deviation of gray-scale values)
Feature 3 Perimeter
Feature 4 Area
Feature 5 Smoothness (local variation in radius lengths)
Feature 6 Compactness (perimeter^2 / area - 1.0)
Feature 7 Concavity (severity of concave portions of the contour)
Feature 8 Concave points (number of concave portions of the contour)
Feature 9 Symmetry
Feature 10 Fractal dimension ("coastline approximation" - 1)

Choosing a measure of success

Input: 569 instances
Output: M = malignant or B = benign
Class distribution: 357 benign, 212 malignant

Recall will be used to measure the success of the model as the class distribution is imbalanced. It is a useful metric when the cost of a false negative prediction is high. In this case, where the positive class is malignant, we want to measure the proportion of correctly predicted malignant cases among all actual malignant cases.

Deciding on an evaluation protocol

We will be using k-fold Cross-Validation as the dataset is relatively small.

Developing a model that does better than a baseline

High recall value may come at the expense of a higher rate of false positives, which may have its own costs and consequences. Therefore, it is important to carefully balance the trade-off between recall and precision, and choose an appropriate value of recall that can achieve the desired level of statistical power while minimizing the overall error rate.

The model can be said to have achieved statistical power when it achieves a recall greater than 0.7.

Compiling the model:

  • Last-layer activation: Sigmoid function
  • Loss function: Binary cross-entropy
  • Optimizer: Adam
In [16]:
# Custom recall function because metrics.Recall() kept incrementing recall key values like: 
# recall_1, recall_2, which made my life difficult for my k-fold validation code below lol
def recall(y_true, y_pred):
    true_positives = K.sum(K.round(K.clip(y_true * y_pred, 0, 1)))
    possible_positives = K.sum(K.round(K.clip(y_true, 0, 1)))
    recall = true_positives / (possible_positives + K.epsilon())
    return recall

def plot(train, val, metric):
    plt.clf()
    plt.figure(figsize=(5, 3))
    epochs = range(1, len(train) + 1)
    plt.plot(epochs, train, 'b', label='Training ' + metric)
    plt.plot(epochs, val, 'r', label='Validation ' + metric)
    plt.title('Training and validation ' + metric)
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.ylabel(metric)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

Scaling up: developing a model that overfits

The ideal model is one that strikes a balance between underfitting and overfitting. To achieve this, we can develop an overfitting model to gain insight into which features and model architectures are causing the overfitting. We can then use this information to adjust the model.

Modifying the model:

  • Add layers
  • Make the layers bigger
  • Train for more epochs
In [24]:

Regularizing the model and tuning the hyperparameters

  • Add or remove layers
  • Add dropout
  • Add L1 and/or L2 regularization
  • Try different hyperparameters to find the optimal configuration
In [29]:
# Deep Learning With Python by Franois Chollet - Chapter 3.6.4 Validating your approach using K-fold validation (modified)
def kFV(k, X_train, y_train, _epochs, _model):
    all_histories = []
    all_evaluation_results = []
    VAL_SIZE = len(X_train) // k
    
    # Prepare validation data from partition k
    for i in range(k):
        print('processing fold #', i)#
        
        # Prepare training data from other partitions
        X_val = X_train[i * VAL_SIZE: (i + 1) * VAL_SIZE]
        y_val = y_train[i * VAL_SIZE: (i + 1) * VAL_SIZE]
        partial_X_train = np.concatenate([X_train[:i * VAL_SIZE], X_train[(i + 1) * VAL_SIZE:]], axis=0)
        partial_y_train = np.concatenate([y_train[:i * VAL_SIZE], y_train[(i + 1) * VAL_SIZE:]], axis=0)
        
        # Build Keras model
        model = _model()
        history = model.fit(partial_X_train, partial_y_train, validation_data=(X_val, y_val), epochs=_epochs, batch_size=32, verbose=0)

        # Extract results
        results = model.evaluate(X_val, y_val, verbose=0)
        all_histories.append(history.history)
        all_evaluation_results.append(results)
    
    # Calculate mean values per epoch
    epochs = len(all_histories[0]['loss'])
    m_loss = [np.mean([x['loss'][i] for x in all_histories]) for i in range(epochs)]
    m_recall = [np.mean([x['recall'][i] for x in all_histories]) for i in range(epochs)]
    m_val_loss = [np.mean([x['val_loss'][i] for x in all_histories]) for i in range(epochs)]
    m_val_recall = [np.mean([x['val_recall'][i] for x in all_histories]) for i in range(epochs)]
    m_eval_loss = np.mean([x[0] for x in all_evaluation_results])
    m_eval_recall = np.mean([x[1] for x in all_evaluation_results])
        
    return m_loss, m_recall, m_val_loss, m_val_recall, m_eval_loss, m_eval_recall

Iteration 1 - Add or remove layers

We are drawing conclusions from the overfit model that having 3 hidden layers causes a moderate degree of overfitting. Hence, we will be removing layers from the model.

In [30]:
# Side by side plots
def plot_2(title1, title2, train1, val1, train2, val2, metric):
    plt.clf()
    fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(10, 3))

    epochs = range(1, len(train1) + 1)
    ax1.plot(epochs, train1, 'b', label='Training ' + metric)
    ax1.plot(epochs, val1, 'r', label='Validation ' + metric)
    ax1.set_title(title1)
    ax1.set_xlabel('Epochs')
    ax1.set_ylabel(metric)
    ax1.legend()

    epochs = range(1, len(train2) + 1)
    ax2.plot(epochs, train2, 'b', label='Training ' + metric)
    ax2.plot(epochs, val2, 'r', label='Validation ' + metric)
    ax2.set_title(title2)
    ax2.set_xlabel('Epochs')
    ax2.set_ylabel(metric)
    ax2.legend()

    plt.show()

def model_1():

    model = Sequential()

    model.add(Dense(16, activation = 'sigmoid'))

    model.compile(optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'binary_crossentropy', metrics = [recall])

We seem to have generated a good fit with model 4. However, there are still ways to improve the model using regularization techniques which I will experiment with below.

Iteration 3 - Add dropout

Adding dropout can help the neural network learn more robust features, as it cannot rely on any single neuron to always be present.

In [35]:
def model_5():
    tf.random.set_seed(42)
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(16, activation='relu', input_shape=(len(FEATURES),)))
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2)
    model.add(Dense(8, activation='sigmoid'))
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2)
    model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=[recall])
    return model

m_loss_5, m_recall_5, m_val_loss_5, m_val_recall_5, m_eval_loss_5, m_eval_recall_5 = kFV(4, X_train, y_train, _epochs=50, _model=model_5)

def model_6():

Evaluation of results

Although there were some fluctuations in the loss values of the evaluation results using test data, the model generally behaved well. The final results showed a slightly better loss percentage and proportionally worse recall percentage compared to the baseline, which is considered a positive outcome. Model 4 had a similar performance to that of model 7, which made me question whether regularization was necessary, and if I should have selected model 4 as the final model instead.
